label.value: decreased population viability in presence of persistent double-strand breaks

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which a smaller than normal proportion of cells in the population is viable when double-strand breaks in DNA are continually made (for example, by constitutive expression of a nuclease).

definition.value: This phenotype is commonly assayed by continuous expression of the HO endonuclease.

label.value: altered double-strand break repair junction in presence of persistent double-strand breaks

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the repair of double-strand breaks in DNA that are continually made (for example, by constitutive expression of a nuclease) results in repair junctions that differ from wild type.

definition.value: This phenotype is commonly assayed using continuous expression of the HO endonuclease, and in mutant cells that survive constitutive DNA cleavage by HO, break repair patterns differ from those in wild type HO survivors.

value.value: A cell phenotype in which spores germinate to a lower extent than wild type following exposure to ionizing radiation.

label.value: decreased protein level during cellular response to salt stress

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of protein measured in a cell during a cellular response to salt stress is lower than normal. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal translation or abnormal regulation of translation, but note that changes in protein levels may result from changes in protein stability or degradation as well as changes in protein synthesis. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell has no septum and is inviable.

definition.value: Note that if you have done an experiment that assays the viability of a population of cells, such as looking at colony growth or growth in liquid culture, you should also annotate to 'inviable cell population' (FYPO:0002059) or one of its descendants.

label.value: normal nuclear 5'-3' exonucleolytic mRNA catabolic process

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which an exonucleolytic RNA catabolic process that proceeds in the 5' to 3' direction to degrade mRNA encoded in the nucleus is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: decreased nuclear 5'-3' exonucleolytic mRNA catabolic process

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of an exonucleolytic RNA catabolic process that proceeds in the 5' to 3' direction to degrade mRNA encoded in the nucleus is decreased.

A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which an RNA catabolic process that degrades mRNA encoded in the nucleus does not occur. Total mRNA or a specific mRNA, such as the mRNA transcribed from a gene of interest, may be affected.

label.value: decreased protein localization to Golgi apparatus, with protein mislocalized to endoplasmic reticulum

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the Golgi apparatus is decreased, and the protein is present in the endoplasmic reticulum instead.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal protein localization to Golgi apparatus

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the Golgi apparatus is abnormal.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which cell population growth is increased relative to normal. Increased growth may reflect an increased growth rate (i.e. faster growth), growth that occurs to a greater extent than normal, or both. Cell population growth refers to an increase in the number of cells in the population as individual cells grow and divide.

label.value: increased cell population growth during glucose starvation

value.value: A cell growth phenotype in which cell population growth is increased relative to normal under conditions of glucose starvation.

definition.value: Note that FYPO uses "glucose starvation" to refer specifically to conditions in which glucose is scarce enough to trigger mating, meiosis, and sporulation. For phenotypes observed in the presence of enough glucose to prevent cells from mating, use a term that specifies "during vegetative growth" plus a condition to indicate low glucose.

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of m7G(5')pppN diphosphatase activity is abnormal.
A molecular function phenotype in which m7G(5')pppN diphosphatase activity is absent.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of m7G(5')pppN diphosphatase activity is decreased.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of m7G(5')pppN diphosphatase activity is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of thioredoxin peroxidase activity is abnormal.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of thioredoxin peroxidase activity is increased.

label.value: increased RNA catabolic process during cellular response to hydrogen peroxide

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of an RNA catabolic process is increased during a cellular response to hydrogen peroxide.

label.value: delayed onset of protein localization to cell division site

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the site of cell division begins later than normal.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the degradation of messenger RNA (mRNA) molecules that contain nonsense mutations is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of sulfite reductase activity is abnormal.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of sulfite reductase activity is decreased.

label.value: decreased protein localization to chromatin at replication origin

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to chromatin at replication origins is decreased.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: delayed onset of protein phosphorylation during cellular response to oxidative stress

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the phosphorylation of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, begins later than normal during a cellular response to oxidative stress.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A metabolism phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which triglyceride biosynthesis is abnormal.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which triglyceride biosynthesis is decreased.
A cellular metabolism phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which triglyceride biosynthesis is increased.
A translation phenotype in which a tRNA pairs with mRNA at the stop codon UAA, and incorporates an amino acid residue into the nascent polypeptide.

A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the posttranscriptional addition of two methyl groups to the N2 position of a guanine residue in a tRNA molecule is abolished. Normally, two methyl groups are transferred to the G26 residue.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of diacylglycerol O-acyltransferase activity is abnormal.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of diacylglycerol O-acyltransferase activity is decreased.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of diacylglycerol O-acyltransferase activity is increased.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of phospholipid:diacylglycerol acyltransferase activity is abnormal.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of phospholipid:diacylglycerol acyltransferase activity is decreased.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a glutathione disulfide oxidoreductase activity is abnormal.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a glutathione disulfide oxidoreductase activity is decreased.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a glutathione disulfide oxidoreductase activity is increased.

label.value: increased protein level during cellular response to salt stress

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of protein measured in a cell during a cellular response to salt stress is higher than normal. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal translation or abnormal regulation of translation, but note that changes in protein levels may result from changes in protein stability or degradation as well as changes in protein synthesis. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased protein level in stationary phase

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of protein measured in a cell is lover than normal when the population in which the cell is found is in stationary phase. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal translation or abnormal regulation of translation, but note that changes in protein levels may result from changes in protein stability or degradation as well as changes in protein synthesis. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: inviable after spore germination, without cell division, with swollen elongated germ tube and bidirectional cell growth from spore body

value.value: A phenotype in which a spore germinates to produce an elongated germ tube that has a larger diameter and volume than normal, then initiates growth from the opposite end of the spore body, and does not go on to form a viable dividing cell. The cell may undergo one or two rounds of nuclear division, but does not undergo cytokinesis.

A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell forms a mitotic spindle in an abnormal location. The normal location is centered at the midpoint of, and parallel to, the long axis of the cell.

label.value: incomplete mitotic sister chromatid segregation, with chromatin bridge

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which mitotic sister chromatid segregation stops before completing separation of chromosomes, and partially separated DNA masses are connected by one or more bridges formed of chromatin.

label.value: inviable after spore germination, multiple cell divisions, with abnormal cytokinetic cell separation and increased septum thickness

value.value: A phenotype in which a spore germinates to produce a cell of that undergoes two or more rounds of cell division in which cells do not completely separate upon cytokinesis, form septa that are thicker than normal, and then die.
A cellular process phenotype in which exit from mitosis is abnormal.

A localization phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which nuclear pore localization is abnormal, resulting in an abnormal spatial arrangement of nuclear pores within the nuclear envelope.

A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which one or more clusters of nuclear pores, associated with membrane fragments derived from the nuclear envelope, are present in the cytoplasm.

A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the nuclear envelope is broken into multiple small fragments, none of which completely surrounds the contents of the nucleus.

label.value: inviable vegetative cell with fragmented nuclear envelope during mitotic telophase

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which a vegetatively growing cell is inviable, and has a nuclear envelope that is broken into multiple small fragments during mitotic telophase.

definition.value: Note that if you have done an experiment that assays the viability of a population of cells, such as looking at colony growth or growth in liquid culture, you should also annotate to 'viable cell population' (FYPO:0002058) or one of its descendants.

label.value: inviable vegetative cell with nuclear pore aggregation in cytoplasm during mitotic telophase

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which a vegetatively growing cell is inviable, and one or more clusters of nuclear pores are present in the cytoplasm during mitotic telophase.

definition.value: Note that if you have done an experiment that assays the viability of a population of cells, such as looking at colony growth or growth in liquid culture, you should also annotate to 'viable cell population' (FYPO:0002058) or one of its descendants.
